VALUES
(42, 20, 22, 40, 22, 17, 21, NULL, 'Tribute to Caesar Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the question of tribute to Caesar, highlighting the challenge posed to Jesus regarding the lawfulness of paying taxes. This thematic parallel underscores the tension between civic duty and religious obligation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 22, 41, 12, 14, 17, 'Is it lawful for us to give tribute unto Cesar, or no?', 'Tribute to Caesar Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the question of tribute to Caesar, highlighting a challenge to Jesus regarding the lawfulness of paying taxes. The phrasing in both texts reflects the same inquiry about giving tribute, linking them thematically.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 23, 40, 22, 18, 18, 'Why tempt ye me', 'Connection of Perception and Temptation', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' awareness of the intentions of those questioning him. The use of ''tempt'' in both verses highlights the challenge posed to Jesus by the hypocritical motives of his interrogators.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 23, 42, 5, 22, 22, NULL, 'Perception of Thoughts', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' ability to perceive thoughts and intentions. In Luke 20:23, He recognizes their craftiness, while in Luke 5:22, He discerns their thoughts, highlighting His insight into human hearts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 23, 46, 3, 19, 19, 'craftiness', 'Craftiness and Divine Wisdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of human craftiness being perceived by God. Both passages emphasize the idea that worldly wisdom, characterized by craftiness, is ultimately foolishness in the eyes of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 23, 19, 95, 9, 9, 'tempt ye me', 'Temptation and Testing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of temptation in both passages. In Luke, Jesus addresses those who tempt him, while in Psalms, the fathers are described as having tempted God, indicating a parallel in the act of testing faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 23, 40, 16, 1, 1, 'tempt ye me', 'Temptation by Religious Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize the act of tempting Jesus by religious leaders. In Luke, Jesus perceives their craftiness, while in Matthew, the Pharisees and Sadducees explicitly seek to tempt him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 23, 42, 6, 8, 8, 'he perceived their craftiness', 'Perception of Thoughts', 'Both passages emphasize the awareness of Jesus regarding the thoughts and intentions of others. In Luke 20:23, he perceives their craftiness, while in Luke 6:8, he knows their thoughts, demonstrating his insight into their motives.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 23, 43, 2, 24, 25, 'he perceived their craftiness', 'Understanding Jesus'' Insight', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' awareness of human intentions. In Luke, he perceives their craftiness, while in John, he knows what is in man.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 24, 40, 18, 28, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Debt and Payment', 'This connection highlights the theme of financial obligation and the consequences of failing to meet it. In both passages, the concept of owing money is central, with Luke referencing a coin associated with Caesar and Matthew depicting a servant demanding payment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 24, 40, 20, 2, 2, 'penny', 'Connection of Monetary Themes', 'This connection highlights the use of ''penny'' in both passages, indicating a focus on monetary value and labor. Both verses emphasize the significance of currency in the context of work and authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 24, 42, 2, 1, 1, 'Cesar’s', 'Connection of Taxation and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Caesar in relation to taxation. The decree from Caesar Augustus in Luke 2:1 sets the stage for the taxation context in which Jesus discusses the image of Caesar in Luke 20:24.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 24, 42, 3, 1, 1, 'Cesar’s', 'Connection of Roman Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Caesar in relation to governance. In Luke 20:24, the mention of Caesar''s image on currency reflects his political power, while Luke 3:1 situates the narrative within the reign of Tiberius Caesar, highlighting the Roman political context.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 24, 44, 11, 28, 28, 'Cesar’s', 'Connection of Caesar References', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Caesar, with Luke referencing Caesar''s image on currency and Acts mentioning Claudius Caesar during a significant event. This connection highlights the political context in which early Christians operated.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 24, 44, 25, 8, 12, 'Cesar’s', 'Connection of Authority and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Cesar in legal matters. In Luke, the image of Cesar represents political power, while in Acts, Paul appeals to Cesar''s judgment seat, highlighting the significance of Roman authority in his trial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 24, 50, 4, 22, 22, 'Cesar’s', 'Connection to Caesar''s Authority', 'This connection highlights the mention of Caesar in both passages, linking the authority of the Roman Empire to the early Christian community. The reference to ''Cesar''s'' in both contexts emphasizes the influence of Roman governance on the lives of believers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 25, 45, 13, 6, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Rendering Dues', 'This connection highlights the theme of rendering what is due to authorities. Both passages emphasize the responsibility of individuals to give tribute and honor to those in positions of governance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 25, 20, 24, 21, 21, 'Render therefore unto Cesar', 'Authority and Respect for Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of rendering respect to both earthly authority and divine authority. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing and honoring the roles of God and the king.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 25, 40, 17, 27, 27, 'render therefore unto Cesar the things', 'Connection of Tax and Obligation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fulfilling obligations to authorities and God. In Luke, Jesus instructs to render to Caesar, while in Matthew, He provides a means to pay the temple tax, highlighting the importance of meeting civic responsibilities.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 25, 40, 22, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the directive to ''Render therefore unto Cesar the things which are Cesar’s; and unto God the things that are God’s.'' This connection highlights the consistent teaching of Jesus regarding the relationship between civic duties and spiritual obligations.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 25, 41, 12, 17, 17, 'Render therefore unto Cesar the things which be Cesar’s', 'Connection of Jesus'' Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the instruction to ''Render... unto Cesar'' and ''unto God the things that are God’s.'' This connection highlights a consistent teaching of Jesus regarding the relationship between civil and divine obligations.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 25, 44, 4, 19, 20, 'unto God the things which be God’s', 'Authority and Obedience to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of prioritizing God''s authority over human authority. Both passages emphasize the necessity of rendering to God what is due to Him, even when faced with human demands.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 25, 44, 5, 29, 29, 'Render therefore unto Cesar', 'Obedience to God vs. Authority', 'This connection highlights the tension between obeying earthly authorities and divine commands. Both passages emphasize the necessity of prioritizing God''s authority over human governance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 26, 42, 20, 20, 20, 'take hold of his words', 'Attempts to Capture Jesus'' Words', 'Both passages emphasize the efforts to take hold of Jesus'' words. In Luke 20:20, spies are sent to capture his words, while in Luke 20:26, they fail to do so, leading to their amazement.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 26, 18, 5, 12, 13, 'they marvelled at his answer', 'Wisdom and Craftiness', 'This connection highlights how both passages emphasize the inability of the crafty and wise to succeed against divine wisdom. In Luke, the people marvel at Jesus'' answer, reflecting how he outsmarts those trying to trap him, similar to Job''s assertion that God frustrates the plans of the crafty.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 26, 20, 26, 4, 5, 'held their peace', 'Wisdom in Responding to Fools', 'This connection highlights the theme of wise responses to foolish challenges. In Luke, the inability to take hold of Jesus'' words reflects a wise avoidance of folly, while Proverbs presents contrasting approaches to engaging with fools.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 26, 40, 22, 12, 12, 'held their peace', 'Silence and Speechlessness', 'This connection highlights the theme of being rendered speechless in the presence of authority. In both passages, individuals are left without a response, either due to amazement or the weight of their situation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 26, 40, 22, 22, 22, 'they marvelled', 'Response to Challenging Questions', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of the people to Jesus'' words, highlighting their amazement. The phrase ''they marvelled'' in both accounts indicates a shared response to his teachings.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 26, 42, 13, 17, 17, 'held their peace', 'Response to Adversaries', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' authority in the face of opposition. Both passages depict adversaries being silenced or ashamed by His words, leading to a positive response from the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 26, 45, 3, 19, 19, 'held their peace', 'Silencing of Arguments', 'This connection highlights the theme of silencing opposition. In Luke, the inability to take hold of Jesus'' words reflects the stopping of mouths mentioned in Romans, emphasizing the authority of God''s law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
